\begin_layout Standard
The history of the neutrino can be traced back to the electron energy spectrum
 observed in neutron 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-decay.
 While measurements of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

- and 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

-decay of atomic nuclei showed discrete spectral lines, the electron (
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 particle) exhibited a continuous energy spectrum.
 Experimentally, there were two observed particles in each decay process
 and classical physics dictated that the outgoing daughter particles should
 have discrete energies.
 The fact that the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-decay spectrum was very different posed a fundamental problem for physicists
 in the mid-1910s, which was that energy was not conserved.
 Two solutions were postulated: either the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

energy conservation law is only valid statistically in such a process [...]
 or an additional undetectable new particle [...] carrying away the additional
 energy and spin [...] is emitted
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Zuber2012"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The latter solution was proposed by Wolfgang Pauli in a letter dated 4
 December 1930 to a group of physicists meeting in Tübingen, modern Germany,
 where he first proposed the neutrino
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In W Pauli's December 1930 letter, he referred to his proposed particle
 as the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

neutron
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, which is not the same neutron that we know of today.
 At that point in time, the neutral particles inside the atomic nucleus,
 also called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

neutrons
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, had not been discovered, let alone understood.
 The neutron, which was discovered in 1932 by James Chadwick, has been formally
 associated as the neutral, cousin particle to the proton.
 It would be Enrico Fermi who would coin the particle in W Pauli's letter
 and solution to the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-decay spectrum as a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

neutrino
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 meaning in Italian 
\shape italic
little neutral one
\shape default
.
\begin_inset VSpace defskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Pauli's solution also predicted that the undetected neutrino would have
 half-integer spin, a quantum mechanical property of matter, since the observed
 particles in 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-decay did not conserve angular momentum.
 The existence of the neutrino and validation of Pauli's predictions would
 not be experimentally verified for another 20 years.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The neutrino was first observed in 1953 by Clyde Cowan and Frederick Reines
 using a nuclear reactor in South Carolina, United States of America.
 Since then three types or 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

flavors
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of neutrinos and antineutrinos have been observed using accelerators and
 also from unique sources like the Sun and a supernova.
 Neutrino physics continues to be an active area of fundamental research
 since the neutrino is a truly unique probe to subatomic processes.
 For instance they are observed to originate from the depths of the Sun's
 core (over 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{7}$
\end_inset

 degrees Kelvin) where fusion occurs.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Neutrinos rarely interact with normal matter, meaning that they travel essential
ly unimpeded towards one's particle detector.
 The rarity of such interactions can be illustrated by the fact that over
 a typical human lifetime, only one solar neutrino interaction with an individua
l is expected out of the 
\begin_inset Formula $7.0\times10^{10}\text{ neutrinos}/\text{cm}^{2}/\text{sec}$
\end_inset

 incident on the Earth.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
To give some perspective to this number, this means 70 billion neutrinos
 are traveling every second through an area similar to one's own thumb nail.
\begin_inset VSpace defskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 So this begs the question: how does one detect a neutrino? The short answer
 is that one requires a large enough flux of neutrinos passing through a
 large dense volume of matter just to detect a single neutrino with today's
 technology.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Scientists continue to be interested in neutrinos due to the unusual properties
 they exhibit.
 One of the more recent and surprising aspects of neutrinos is their ability
 to undergo 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

flavor oscillations
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 where a neutrino of definite flavor (type) is created and later observed
 as a different flavor.
 The impact of differences between neutrino and antineutrino oscillations
 could help explain the observed matter-antimatter asymmetry in the Universe
 which one of the most profound mysteries in physics today.
\end_layout

