\begin_layout Standard
The name 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

weak force
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 comes from the fact that this force is much weaker than the electromagnetic
 and strong nuclear forces.
 This is due to the weak mediating bosons, the 
\begin_inset Formula $W^{\pm}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

, being massive particles unlike the massless gluon (g) and photon (
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

).
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $W^{\pm}/Z$
\end_inset

 have masses of 80/90 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{GeV/c}^{2}$
\end_inset

, which is more massive than all the other elementary particles except for
 the top quark.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For weak interactions to occur at energies far below the masses (also called
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

off-shell
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) of the 
\begin_inset Formula $W^{\pm}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

, the interaction time must be infinitesimally small as dictated by the
 Heisenberg Uncertainty Principle
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Delta E\Delta t\gtrsim\hbar\label{eq:heisenberguncertainty}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta E$
\end_inset

 is the energy of the particle and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta t$
\end_inset

 is the time during which the particle exists.
 As an example, consider a neutrino emitting a Z-boson as shown in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "fig:CCNCInteractions"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 If the energy of the neutrino is 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 GeV, the lifetime of the 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 boson is about 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{-25}$
\end_inset

 seconds according to 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "eq:heisenberguncertainty"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 In general, the probability that a massive particle of mass 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 will be created from the collision of two particles is given by a relativistic
 Breit–Wigner distribution
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f(M)\propto\frac{1}{\left(M^{2}-M_{0}^{2}\right)^{2}c^{4}+M_{0}^{2}\Gamma^{2}},\label{eq:BreitWigner}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{0}$
\end_inset

 is the rest mass and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

 is the decay width of the particle.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $M\ll M_{0}$
\end_inset

, the probability of creating that particle will be infinitesimally small.
 Therefore to observe a single weak interaction requires a large number
 of weakly interacting particles.
\end_layout

