\begin_layout Standard
Neutrinos are observed to have their spin direction vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\sigma}$
\end_inset

 opposite to their momentum 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{P}$
\end_inset

 and this is reversed for antineutrinos.
 This property is called helicity and is given by 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "eq:helicityoperator"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{H}=\frac{\boldsymbol{\sigma}\cdot\boldsymbol{P}}{\left|\boldsymbol{P}\right|}.\label{eq:helicityoperator}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Although neutrino detection is difficult, the neutrino helicity is readily
 inferred from the daughter muon's helicity in pion decay, 
\begin_inset Formula $\pion^{+}\rightarrow\mu^{+}+\numu$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $\muplus$
\end_inset

 has negative helicity (
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}=-1$
\end_inset

) and to converse spin, the neutrino's helicity must also be negative as
 shown in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "fig:DecayOfPion"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 The antineutrino's helicity is positive (+1) as shown in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "fig:DecayOfPion"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 through use of the charge (C) conjugation and parity (P) transformations.
 A C conjugation is a linear transformation that transforms all particles
 into their corresponding antiparticles while the P transformation inverts
 all spatial coordinates.
 Thus neutrinos are referred to as 
\shape italic
left-handed
\shape default
 (LH) particles while antineutrinos are referred to as 
\shape italic
right-handed
\shape default
 (RH) particles.
 It turns out that helicity is a useful quantum number to describe neutrinos
 and coincides with a property called chirality.
 To understand chirality and its relationship to helicity requires an analysis
 of the Dirac Lagrangian and Dirac equation.
\end_layout

