\begin_layout Standard
The Dirac Lagrangian for a free particle field 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 with half-integer spin can be written as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{L}=\overline{\psi}\left(x\right)\left[\frac{i\hbar}{2}\sum_{\mu=0}^{3}\gamma^{\mu}\left(\overrightarrow{\partial_{\mu}}-\overleftarrow{\partial_{\mu}}\right)-mc\right]\psi\left(x\right)\label{eq:diraclagrangian}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 is a four-component vector (spinor) describing a particle field and 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma^{\mu}$
\end_inset

 are a set of four 4x4 matrices.
 The adjoint field 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\psi}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 is defined as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\overline{\psi}\left(x\right)\equiv\psi^{\dagger}\left(x\right)\gamma^{0}\label{eq:adjointfield}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\dagger$
\end_inset

 denotes the conjugate and transpose operations.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $\overrightarrow{\partial_{\mu}}$
\end_inset

 operator is a four-vector defined as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\partial_{0}=\frac{1}{c}\partderiv t,\partial_{1}=\partderiv x,\partial_{2}=\partderiv y,\partial_{3}=\partderiv z\label{eq:fourderivative}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

that acts only to the right while 
\begin_inset Formula $\overleftarrow{\partial_{\mu}}$
\end_inset

 only acts to the left (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\psi}\overleftarrow{\partial_{\mu}}=\partial_{\mu}\overline{\psi}$
\end_inset

).
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma^{\mu}$
\end_inset

 matrices are not unique and different representations are more appropriate
 for different kinematic regimes.
 The field equations are extracted from the Lagrangian using the Euler-Lagrange
 procedure.
 In general for a set of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 fields, the field equations are given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\partial_{\mu}\frac{\partial\mathcal{L}}{\partial\left(\partial_{\mu}\psi_{r}\right)}-\frac{\partial\mathcal{L}}{\partial\psi_{r}}=0\quad\left(r=0,1,2,\ldots,M-1,M\right).\label{eq:eulerlagrangegeneral}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 For the Dirac Lagrangian, the field equation for 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\partial_{\mu}\frac{\partial\mathcal{L}}{\partial\left(\partial_{\mu}\overline{\psi}\right)}-\frac{\partial\mathcal{L}}{\partial\overline{\psi}}=0\label{eq:diracELequation}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which yields the Dirac equation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left[i\hbar\sum_{\mu=0}^{3}\gamma^{\mu}\partial_{\mu}-mc\right]\psi\left(x\right)=0.\label{eq:diraceqn}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The representation of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma^{\mu}$
\end_inset

 matrices that is useful to describe neutrinos is the 
\shape italic
Chiral representation
\shape default
 (also called the 
\shape italic
Weyl representation
\shape default
) where
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\gamma^{0}=\begin{bmatrix}0 & I_{2}\\
I_{2} & 0
\end{bmatrix},\gamma^{1}=\begin{bmatrix}0 & \sigma_{x}\\
-\sigma_{x} & 0
\end{bmatrix},\gamma^{2}=\begin{bmatrix}0 & \sigma_{y}\\
-\sigma_{y} & 0
\end{bmatrix},\gamma^{3}=\begin{bmatrix}0 & \sigma_{z}\\
-\sigma_{z} & 0
\end{bmatrix},\label{eq:gammamatrices}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $I_{2}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $2\times2$
\end_inset

 identity matrix, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{x,y,z}$
\end_inset

 are the Pauli Spin matrices given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sigma_{x}=\sigma_{1}=\begin{pmatrix}0 & 1\\
1 & 0
\end{pmatrix},\quad\sigma_{y}=\sigma_{2}=\begin{pmatrix}0 & -i\\
i & 0
\end{pmatrix},\quad\sigma_{z}=\sigma_{3}=\begin{pmatrix}1 & 0\\
0 & -1
\end{pmatrix}.
\]

\end_inset

Using the Chiral representation, the chirality matrix, 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma^{5}$
\end_inset

 (the fifth gamma matrix), is defined as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\gamma^{5}=i\gamma^{0}\gamma^{1}\gamma^{2}\gamma^{3}=\begin{bmatrix}-I_{2} & 0\\
0 & I_{2}
\end{bmatrix},\label{eq:gammafivedef}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which is diagonal as well as Hermitian, meaning that its eigenvalues are
 real and observable.
 Let the eigenfunctions of the chirality matrix be denoted with subscripts
 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 such that the eigenvalue equations are
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{aligned}\gamma^{5}\psi_{P} & =+1\psi_{P},\\
\gamma^{5}\psi_{M} & =-1\psi_{M}.
\end{aligned}
\label{eq:chiraloperatoreigenvalueequation}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The field equation solutions to 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "eq:diraceqn"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 can be decomposed into 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{P}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{M}$
\end_inset

 projections using two chiral projection operators 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{O}_{P,M}$
\end_inset

 where
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\psi=\left(\hat{O}_{P}+\hat{O}_{M}\right)\psi=\psi_{P}+\psi_{M}.\label{eq:chiralprojections}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The chiral operators are explicitly given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{aligned}\hat{O}_{M} & =\frac{1}{2}\left(I_{4}-\gamma^{5}\right)=\begin{pmatrix}0 & 0\\
0 & I_{2}
\end{pmatrix},\\
\hat{O}_{P} & =\frac{1}{2}\left(I_{4}+\gamma^{5}\right)=\begin{pmatrix}I_{2} & 0\\
0 & 0
\end{pmatrix},
\end{aligned}
\label{eq:chiraloperators}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{4}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $4\times4$
\end_inset

 identity matrix.
 Taken together 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "eq:chiralprojections"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "eq:chiraloperators"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 indicate the free neutrino field is a vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 minus axial vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma^{5}\psi$
\end_inset

, also referred to as V-A, under P transformations.
 This feature is what allows for the weak force to violate P-symmetry and
 CP-symmetry.
 Referring back to
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "eq:diraclagrangian"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "eq:eulerlagrangegeneral"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, the Dirac equation becomes a set of coupled equations
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{aligned}i\hbar\sum_{\mu=0}^{3}\gamma^{\mu}\partial_{\mu}\psi_{P} & =mc\psi_{M},\\
i\hbar\sum_{\mu=0}^{3}\gamma^{\mu}\partial_{\mu}\psi_{M} & =mc\psi_{P}
\end{aligned}
\label{eq:diraceqnchiral}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where dynamics are set by the mass.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since the chiral projection operators are decompositions of the identity
 matrix, the simplest nontrivial solution to 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\psi=\begin{pmatrix}\chi_{P}\\
\chi_{M}
\end{pmatrix}\label{eq:diracchiralspinorsgeneral}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi$
\end_inset

 represent two-component spinors.
 Using 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:diracchiralspinorsgeneral"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 the Dirac equation in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "eq:diraceqnchiral"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 can again be rewritten as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{aligned}i\hbar\left[\frac{1}{c}\partderiv t+\boldsymbol{\sigma}\cdot\boldsymbol{\nabla}\right]\chi_{P} & =-mc\chi_{M},\\
i\hbar\left[\frac{1}{c}\partderiv t-\boldsymbol{\sigma}\cdot\boldsymbol{\nabla}\right]\chi_{M} & =-mc\chi_{P},
\end{aligned}
\label{eq:diraceqnchiralspinors}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{\sigma}\cdot\boldsymbol{\nabla}=\sigma_{x}\partderiv x+\sigma_{y}\partderiv y+\sigma_{z}\partderiv z.\label{eq:matrixdotproduct}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

In the limiting case of vanishing mass 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(m\rightarrow0\right)$
\end_inset

, as is in the SM, the free particle field equations in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "eq:diraceqnchiralspinors"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 decouple into
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{aligned}\left(\frac{E}{c}+\boldsymbol{\sigma}\cdot\boldsymbol{P}\right)\chi_{P} & =0,\\
\left(\frac{E}{c}-\boldsymbol{\sigma}\cdot\boldsymbol{P}\right)\chi_{M} & =0,
\end{aligned}
\label{eq:diraceqnchiralmassless}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the differential operators have been evaluated as the particle's energy
 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 and momentum three-vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{P}$
\end_inset

.
 For massless neutrinos, 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{P}$
\end_inset

 and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{P}$
\end_inset

, describe particles of negative energy 
\begin_inset Formula $E=-\left|\boldsymbol{P}\right|c$
\end_inset

 in the context of quantum field theory are interpreted as antiparticles
 traveling backwards in time.
 Conversely, 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{M}$
\end_inset

 have positive energy 
\begin_inset Formula $E=\left|\boldsymbol{P}\right|c$
\end_inset

 and which means they are particles traveling forward in time.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If one also multiplies 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "eq:diraceqnchiral"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma^{5}\gamma^{0}$
\end_inset

 and uses the fact that the spin operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\boldsymbol{\sigma}}$
\end_inset

 is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{\sigma}=i\left(\gamma^{2}\gamma^{3},\gamma^{3}\gamma^{1},\gamma^{1}\gamma^{2}\right)=\gamma^{0}\gamma^{k}\gamma^{5}\quad\left(k=1,2,3\right)\label{eq:spinoperatorgammamatrices}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

each decoupled equation becomes
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\boldsymbol{\sigma}\cdot\boldsymbol{P}}{\left|\boldsymbol{P}\right|}\psi_{P,M}=\gamma^{5}\psi_{P,M}=\pm\psi_{P,M},\label{eq:chiralhelicityrelationship}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where one recognizes that the helicity and chiral states are the same for
 
\begin_inset Formula $m\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

 only.
 Thus the labels 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 actually are identical to the LH and RH helicity labels, respectively.
 Using the results above, a neutrino is always observed as a LH particle
 while the antineutrino is always observed as a RH antiparticle.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The observation of only LH neutrinos and RH antineutrinos is an important
 feature in the SM.
 However, since neutrinos are known to have mass, given that neutrinos oscillate
, it is theoretically possible to observe a RH neutrino and a LH antineutrino.
 That would require boosting to a highly relativistic reference frame with
 respect to the laboratory.
\end_layout

