\begin_layout Standard
In the general case of oscillations using a 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times n$
\end_inset

 mixing matrix, the unitary transformation can be written as a rotation
 matrix with 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{n}{2}(n-1)$
\end_inset

 weak mixing angles with 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{2}(n-2)(n-1)$
\end_inset

 Charge-Parity (CP) violating phases.
 In addition, oscillations are dictated by a total of 
\begin_inset Formula $n-1$
\end_inset

 mass-squared splittings
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Zuber2012"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 This all assumes that neutrinos obey the Dirac Equation, or that they are
 not their own antiparticles.
 The favored mixing model is a 
\begin_inset Formula $3\times3$
\end_inset

 matrix since there are three known neutrino flavors, 
\begin_inset Formula $\nue$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\numu$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nutau$
\end_inset

.
 This means that there are three (3) mixing angles, one (1) CP violating
 phase, and three (3) mass-squared splittings.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The most frequently used matrix parameterization is the MNSP (MNSP: Maki-Nakagaw
a-Sakata-Pontecorvo) matrix.
 Pontecorvo is credited with first conceiving of neutrino oscillations,
 albeit between neutrino and antineutrinos
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Ponte1957"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 It was Maki, Nakagawa, and Sakata who conceived of the parameterization
 based on the ideas of Pontecorvo
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Maki1962"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The MNSP matrix is decomposed into separate rotation matrices as given
 by 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "eq:mnspdecomposed"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{aligned}U_{\text{MNSP}} & =\stackrel{U_{32}=U_{\text{atm}}}{\overbrace{\begin{bmatrix}\begin{array}{rrr}
1 & 0 & 0\\
0 & c_{32} & s_{32}\\
0 & -s_{32} & c_{32}
\end{array}\end{bmatrix}}}\times\stackrel{U_{31}=U_{\text{rea}}}{\overbrace{\begin{bmatrix}c_{31} & 0 & s_{31}e^{i\delta_{\text{CP}}}\\
0 & 1 & 0\\
-s_{31}e^{-i\delta_{\text{CP}}} & 0 & c_{31}
\end{bmatrix}}}\times\stackrel{U_{21}=U_{\text{sol}}}{\overbrace{\begin{bmatrix}\begin{array}{rrr}
c_{21} & s_{21} & 0\\
-s_{21} & c_{21} & 0\\
0 & 0 & 1
\end{array}\end{bmatrix}}}\end{aligned}
,\label{eq:mnspdecomposed}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\cc{ij}=\cos\theta_{ij},\quad\ss{ij}=\sin\theta_{ij},\label{eq:cossinshorthand}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{\text{CP}}$
\end_inset

 represents the CP violating phase.
 Each rotation matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{ij}$
\end_inset

 represents the different sources for neutrino oscillations experiments
 with 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

atm
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

rea
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

sol
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

