\begin_layout Standard
If neutrinos are their own antiparticles, they are not described by the
 Dirac Equation but instead are described the Majorana Equation.
 This adds two (in general 
\begin_inset Formula $n-1$
\end_inset

) more CP violating Majorana phases, 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

, to the MNSP matrix
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
U_{\text{MNSP}}\rightarrow U_{\text{MNSP}}\times\stackrel{U_{\text{Majorana}}}{\overbrace{\begin{bmatrix}1 & 0 & 0\\
0 & e^{i\alpha} & 0\\
0 & 0 & e^{i\beta}
\end{bmatrix}}}.\label{eq:mnspdecomposedmajorana}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Unfortunately, neutrino oscillations are not able to probe the Majorana
 phases since the Majorana matrix is diagonal.
 The question of as to whether neutrinos are Majorana (
\begin_inset Formula $\nu=\overline{\nu})$
\end_inset

 or Dirac (
\begin_inset Formula $\nu\neq\overline{\nu})$
\end_inset

 particles is an open question that is being explored by neutrino-less double
 beta decay experiments
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "1982PhRvD..25.2951S"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The full three flavor oscillation probability is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{aligned}\mathcal{P}\left(\nu_{\alpha}\rightarrow\nu_{\beta}\right)=\delta_{\alpha\beta}-4 & \sum_{j=1}^{3}\left[\sum_{i>j}^{3}\text{Re}\left(K_{\alpha\beta,ij}\right)\sin^{2}\left(\phi_{ij}\right)\right]\\
+4 & \sum_{j=1}^{3}\left[\sum_{i>j}^{3}\text{Im}\left(K_{\alpha\beta,ij}\right)\sin\left(\phi_{ij}\right)\cos\left(\phi_{ij}\right)\right]
