\begin_layout Standard
The ND280 magnetic field permits the measurements of particle charge and
 momentum.
 A particle of charge 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

, rest mass 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{0}$
\end_inset

, and velocity 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 under the influence of an external electric and magnetic fields, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{E}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{B}$
\end_inset

, respectively, experiences a force 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{F}$
\end_inset

 given by the Lorentz force equation
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{F}=q\left(\mathbf{E}+\mathbf{v}\times\mathbf{B}\right).\label{eq:Lorentzforce}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Assuming for now that there is no external electric field, the force on
 the particle is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{F}=q\mathbf{v}\times\mathbf{B},\label{eq:LorentzforceNoE}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which is both orthogonal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{B}$
\end_inset

.
 Since the mechanical work on a particle in a magnetic field is zero, the
 particle's energy is unchanged (
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\mathbf{v}\right|$
\end_inset

 = 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 = constant).
 Newton's Second Law allows us to rewrite the force as an change in momentum
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{P}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{aligned}\mathbf{F} & =\frac{d\mathbf{P}}{dt}\\
 & =\frac{d}{dt}\left(\gamma(v)m_{0}\mathbf{v}\right)\\
 & =m_{0}\mathbf{v}\left(\frac{d\gamma(v)}{dt}\right)+\gamma(v)m_{0}\left(\frac{d\mathbf{v}}{dt}\right)\\
 & =m_{0}\mathbf{v}\left(\frac{d\gamma(v)}{dv}\right)\cancelto{0}{\left(\frac{dv}{dt}\right)}+\gamma(v)m_{0}\mathbf{a}\\
 & =\gamma(v)m_{0}\mathbf{\mathbf{a}},
\end{aligned}
\label{eq:relativisticforceInBfield}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{P=\gamma}(v)m_{0}\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is the relativistic momentum and 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(v)=\left(1-\left(v/c\right)^{2}\right)^{\nicefrac{-1}{2}}$
\end_inset

 is the Lorentz factor for relativistic particles.
 For uniform circular motion, the magnitude of the acceleration is given
 by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left|\mathbf{a}\right|=v^{2}/R,\label{eq:uniformcircularmotion}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where R is the radius of curvature for the circle.
 Combining 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:uniformcircularmotion"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:relativisticforceInBfield"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 with some algebra yields
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
R=\frac{\gamma(v)m_{0}v}{q\left|\mathbf{B}\right|\sin\theta_{\mathbf{vB}}},\label{eq:radiusofcurvature}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{\mathbf{vB}}$
\end_inset

 is the angle between 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{B}$
\end_inset

.
 The numerator of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:radiusofcurvature"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is recognized as the magnitude of the momentum 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\mathbf{P}\right|$
\end_inset

.
 Some further rearrangement yields
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left|\mathbf{P}\right|=q\left|\mathbf{B}\right|R\sin\theta_{\mathbf{vB}},\label{eq:momentuminmagneticfield}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and thus measuring the direction and radius of curvature inside the field
 provides the charge and momentum, respectively, as desired.
\end_layout

