\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{23}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta m_{23}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 This is performed by fitting the oscillation parameters to the number of
 observed flavored neutrinos at SK.
 The number of reconstructed neutrino events of flavor 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{\nu_{\alpha}}$
\end_inset

, observed is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
N_{\nu_{\alpha}}=B+S_{\nu_{\alpha}}\label{eq:Nsigplusbkg}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 are all misidentified 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 events and 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{\nu_{\alpha}}$
\end_inset

is the number of true events.
 The expected reconstructed neutrino appearance rate is given by
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{aligned}S_{\nu_{\alpha}} & =\sum_{\lambda=e,\mu}\left[\mathcal{P}_{\nu_{\lambda}\rightarrow\nu_{\alpha}}\left(E_{\nu};\vec{o}\right)\right]\times\sum_{t}\left[\sigma_{\nu_{\alpha}}^{t}\left(E_{\nu}\right)\cdot t_{N}\right]\\
 & \times\Phi_{\nu_{\alpha}}\left(E_{\nu}\right)\times\epsilon\left(p_{\alpha},\theta_{\alpha}\right),
\end{aligned}
\label{eq:Nsig}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{o}$
\end_inset

 is a vector of the oscillation parameters from 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:threeflavorprobgeneral"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{\nu_{\alpha}}^{t}$
\end_inset

 is the cross section for 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 on target 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{N}$
\end_inset

 is the number of targets of type 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi_{\nu_{\alpha}}$
\end_inset

 is the flux of neutrinos, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon\left(p_{\alpha},\cos\theta_{\alpha}\right)$
\end_inset

 is the efficiency of reconstructing and correctly categorizing the event
 as a function of momentum 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and angle 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
